		<meta
			http-equiv="refresh"
			content="0;url=mailto:itrules.consultation@meity.gov.in,moeit@gov.in,minister.inb@gov.in,mos-eit@gov.in,secretary.meity@gov.in,js-akumar@meity.gov.in,gccyberlaw@meity.gov.in,mos-moib@gov.in,secy.inb@nic.in?cc=KhiKhi@internetfreedom.in&subject=Comments%20to%20the%20Ministry%20of%20Electronics%20and%20Information%20Technology%20on%20the%20Draft%20Information%20Technology%20(Intermediary%20Guidelines%20and%20Digital%20Media%20Ethics%20Code)%20Second%20Amendment%20Rules%2C%202026&body=Dear%20Sir%2FMadam%2C%0A%0AI%20am%20writing%20to%20express%20my%20concerns%20regarding%20the%20Draft%20Information%20Technology%20(Intermediary%20Guidelines%20and%20Digital%20Media%20Ethics%20Code)%20Second%20Amendment%20Rules%2C%202026%20(%22Draft%20Amendments%22)%20which%20amend%20certain%20rules%20in%20the%20Information%20Technology%20(Intermediary%20Guidelines%20and%20Digital%20Media%20Ethics%20Code)%20Rules%2C%202021%20(%22IT%20Rules%2C%202021%22).%0A%0AMy%20feedback%2Fcomments%20on%20the%20Draft%20Amendments%20in%20a%20clause-by-clause%20manner%20are%20as%20follows%3A%0A%0A1.%20Mandatory%20retention%20obligations%20under%20Rules%203(1)(g)%20and%203(1)(h)%3A%20This%20amendment%20indicates%20that%20intermediaries%2Fplatforms%20will%20have%20to%20retain%20user%20data%20when%20they%20register%20for%20a%20computer%20resource%20for%20a%20period%20of%20180%20days.%20Even%20though%20India%27s%20data%20protection%20law%20states%20that%20personal%20data%20obtained%20to%20provide%20certain%20services%20ought%20to%20be%20erased%20upon%20satisfaction%20of%20the%20%22specified%20purpose%22%20for%20which%20such%20data%20was%20obtained.%20This%20requirement%20of%20erasure%20does%20not%20apply%20if%20retention%20is%20necessary%20for%20%22compliance%22%20with%20any%20law.%20Mandating%20storage%20of%20user%20data%20for%20longer%20periods%20increases%20the%20risk%20of%20data%20breaches%2C%20especially%20when%20sensitive%20user%20information%20is%20kept%20for%20extended%20periods%20of%20time.%0A%0ARecommendation%3A%20This%20proposed%20amendment%20must%20be%20withdrawn%20entirely.%20Data%20should%20only%20be%20retained%20for%20specific%2C%20lawful%20purposes%20and%20not%20for%20vague%20or%20general%20use.%20Therefore%2C%20intermediaries%20should%20be%20required%20to%20disclose%20data%20retention%20practices%20if%20beyond%20the%20stipulated%20180-day%20period%2C%20including%20how%20long%20data%20is%20stored%20and%20under%20what%20legal%20basis%20under%20any%20other%20law%20for%20the%20time%20being%20in%20force.%20Moreover%2C%20principles%20under%20the%20Digital%20Personal%20Data%20Protection%20Act%2C%202023%2C%20including%20data%20minimisation%2C%20erasure%20upon%20exhaustion%20of%20%22specified%20purpose%22%20of%20data%20collection%2C%20i.e.%20purpose%20limitation%20must%20be%20accounted%20for.%0A%0A2.%20Insertion%20of%20Rule%203(4)%20mandating%20compliance%20by%20intermediaries%20with%20MeitY-issued%20clarifications%2C%20advisories%2C%20directions%2C%20SOPs%2C%20codes%20of%20practice%20and%20guidelines%2C%20forming%20part%20of%20due%20diligence%20under%20section%2079%3A%20This%20rule%20requires%20intermediaries%20to%20comply%20with%20a%20range%20of%20executive-issued%20clarifications%2C%20advisories%2C%20directions%2C%20standard%20operating%20procedures%2C%20codes%20of%20practice%2C%20and%20guidelines%2C%20to%20retain%20their%20safe%20harbour%20protection%20under%20Section%2079%20of%20the%20IT%20Act.%20There%20are%20several%20issues%20with%20such%20a%20vague%20and%20overbroad%20provision%20mandating%20compliance%20with%20a%20range%20of%20secretive%2C%20ad-hoc%2C%20and%20executive-issued%20instruments.%0A%E2%97%8F%20First%2C%20it%20lowers%20the%20constitutional%20threshold%20for%20intermediary%20due%20diligence%20obligations%20established%20in%20Shreya%20Singhal%20v.%20Union%20of%20India%2C%20by%20treating%20MeitY%27s%20clarifications%2C%20advisories%2C%20directions%2C%20or%20SOPs%2C%20etc.%20at%20par%20with%20judicial%20determinations%20and%20government%20notifications.%0A%E2%97%8F%20Second%2C%20even%20though%20Rule%203(4)(b)%20indicates%20that%20any%20such%20order%2C%20notice%2C%20clarification%2C%20advisory%2C%20SOP%2C%20code%20or%20practice%2C%20or%20guideline%20shall%20be%20issued%20in%20writing%20and%20specify%20statutory%20legal%20basis%2C%20specify%20scope%2C%20and%20be%20consistent%20with%20Act%20and%20Rules%2C%20no%20other%20legal%20instrument%20barring%20amendments%20to%20the%20Act%20and%20the%20rules%20under%20Section%2087%20undergo%20parliamentary%20scrutiny.%0A%E2%97%8F%20Third%2C%20there%20is%20no%20requirement%20that%20any%20such%20order%2C%20notice%2C%20clarification%2C%20advisory%2C%20SOP%2C%20code%20or%20practice%2C%20or%20guideline%20shall%20be%20made%20public.%20Previously%2C%20MeitY%20had%20privately%20issued%20a%20letter%20to%20X%20Corp%2FGrok%20on%2002%20January%202026%2C%20citing%20a%20failure%20to%20comply%20with%20statutory%20due%20diligence%20obligations%20under%20the%20IT%20Act%20and%20the%20IT%20Rules%2C%202021s.%0A%0ARecommendation%3A%20This%20proposed%20amendment%20must%20be%20withdrawn%20entirely.%20%20Rule%203(4)%20should%20be%20withdrawn%20in%20its%20entirety.%20Any%20framework%20governing%20intermediary%20obligations%20must%20remain%20consistent%20with%20the%20standard%20established%20in%20Shreya%20Singhal%20v.%20Union%20of%20India%2C%20and%20should%20not%20permit%20informal%20or%20executive-issued%20instructions%20to%20determine%20intermediary%20liability.%20Further%2C%20the%20proposed%20rule%20suffers%20from%20arbitrariness%20for%20not%20being%20in%20conformity%20with%20the%20rule%20making%20provisions%20prescribed%20under%20the%20IT%20Act.%20Therefore%2C%20the%20MeitY%20must%20withdraw%20this%20proposed%20amendment%20in%20its%20entirety.%0A%0A3.%20Rule%208(1)%20expands%20applicability%20of%20Rules%2014%2C%2015%2C%20and%2016%20to%20news%20and%20current%20affairs%20content%20hosted%20by%20users%20who%20are%20not%20%22publishers%22%3A%0A%E2%97%8F%20The%20expansion%20of%20Rules%2014%2C%2015%2C%20and%2016%20to%20users%20who%20are%20not%20%22publishers%22%20but%20share%20news%20and%20current%20affairs%20content%20is%20an%20attempt%20to%20bring%20both%20intermediaries%20and%20user-generated%20news%20under%20the%20MIB%27s%20blocking%20powers%20and%20the%20jurisdiction%20of%20the%20Inter-Departmental%20Committee%20(IDC)%20under%20Part%20III%20of%20the%20IT%20Rules%2C%202021s.%0A%0ARecommendation%3A%20This%20proposed%20amendment%20must%20be%20withdrawn%20entirely.%20Any%20regulation%20of%20user-generated%20content%20should%20follow%20established%20legal%20processes%2C%20including%20those%20under%20Section%2069A%20of%20the%20IT%20Act%2C%20and%20should%20not%20be%20routed%20through%20indirect%20mechanisms.%20Therefore%2C%20the%20scope%20of%20Rule%208(1)%20should%20be%20restricted%20to%20publishers%2C%20as%20originally%20intended%2C%20and%20should%20not%20extend%20to%20user-generated%20content%20on%20intermediary%20platforms.%20Therefore%2C%20such%20amendment%20to%20the%20proviso%20should%20be%20withdrawn%20in%20its%20entirety.%0A%0A4.%20Rule%2014%20to%20expand%20the%20scope%20and%20functioning%20of%20the%20IDC%20to%20hear%20%22matters%22%20referred%20by%20MIB%3A%0A%E2%97%8F%20Rule%2014(2)%20presently%20requires%20the%20IDC%20to%20hear%20%22complaints%20regarding%20violation%20or%20contravention%20of%20the%20Code%20of%20Ethics%22.%20These%20are%20complaints%20and%20grievances%20from%20users.%0A%E2%97%8F%20The%20IDC%20now%20hears%3A%20(a)%20grievances%20arising%20from%20decisions%20at%20Level%20I%20or%20II%20(from%20users)%3B%20or%20(b)%20%22matters%22%20referred%20to%20by%20the%20Ministry.%20Clause%20(b)%20is%20unconstrained%20since%3A%0Ai.%20there%20is%20no%20requirement%20that%20the%20%22matter%22%20arise%20from%20a%20complaint%2C%0Aii.%20no%20requirement%20that%20the%20%22matter%22%20relate%20to%20a%20Code%20of%20Ethics%20violation%3B%20and%0Aiii.%20no%20requirement%20that%20the%20affected%20party%20be%20heard%20before%20the%20referral.%0A%E2%97%8F%20The%20IDC%20effectively%20now%20operates%20as%20a%20free-standing%20censorship%20committee%20that%20can%20take%20up%20%22matters%22%20referred%20to%20by%20the%20executive.%20Given%20the%20current%20surge%20in%20takedown%20notices%20this%20year%2C%20such%20expansion%20raises%20further%20concerns%20on%20the%20freedom%20of%20speech%20enumerated%20under%20Article%2019(1)(a)%20of%20the%20Constitution%20of%20India.%0A%0ARecommendation%3A%20This%20proposed%20amendment%20must%20be%20withdrawn%20entirely.%20Section%2069A%20and%20Section%2079%20of%20the%20IT%20Act%20are%20the%20two%20provisions%20that%20allow%20for%20blocking%20mechanisms.%20Section%2069A%20provides%20for%20the%20original%20blocking%20mechanism%20and%20Section%2079%20acts%20as%20an%20exemption%20provision%20(not%20an%20independent%20censorship%20mechanism).%20The%20minimal%20procedural%20safeguards%20enumerated%20under%20Section%2069A%20are%20already%20being%20diluted.%20First%2C%20the%20government%20is%20increasingly%20relying%20on%20Section%2079(3)(b)%20of%20the%20IT%20Act%2C%20read%20with%20Rule%203(1)(d)%20of%20the%20IT%20Rules%2C%202021s%2C%20to%20compel%20intermediaries%20to%20remove%20content.%20On%20top%20of%20it%20the%20current%20draft%20amendments%20allow%20the%20IDC%20to%20now%20operate%20as%20a%20free-standing%20censorship%20committee%20that%20can%20take%20up%20%22matters%22%20referred%20to%20by%20the%20executive.%20Together%2C%20this%20forms%20a%20chilling%20effect%2C%20this%20means%20that%20people%20may%20refrain%20from%20expressing%20themselves%20online%20due%20to%20the%20fear%20of%20their%20content%20or%20entire%20account%20being%20taken%20down.%20Such%20a%20climate%20not%20only%20erodes%20individual%20liberty%20but%20also%20dilutes%20the%20essence%20of%20democracy%20by%20curbing%20public%20debate%2C%20criticism%2C%20and%20activism.%20Therefore%2C%20the%20MeitY%20must%20withdraw%20this%20proposed%20amendment%20in%20its%20entirety.%0A%0ABest%20Regards%2C%0A%5BName%5D"
		/>
	</head>
